{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/melanoma-pigmented-lesions/supporting-evidence/evidence-on-self-examination-for-early-melanoma-detection/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"68448720-3dbd-530e-bf51-0c8d618ee81e","slug":"evidence-on-self-examination-for-early-melanoma-detection","fullItemName":"Evidence on self-examination for early melanoma detection","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field c2915138-8828-46bb-86de-97e2c1ee1dd5 --><h2>Evidence on self-examination for early melanoma detection</h2><!-- end field c2915138-8828-46bb-86de-97e2c1ee1dd5 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 419b09bd-785a-4cb2-a6bf-b98f6452efbb --><!-- begin field 091caf9b-d1ee-4b97-9f80-e8623dccee9c --><p><strong>CKS identified evidence which suggests that for people who perform skin self-examination, diagnosis of melanoma is made earlier and melanomas are thinner at diagnosis. In addition to traditional techniques of physical examination (including self-examination), there are now multiple novel methods using novel technology which requires further evaluation. </strong></p><ul><li>The American Academy of Dermatology [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/melanoma-pigmented-lesions/references/\">American Academy of Dermatology, 2015</a>] concluded that the ABCD(E) criteria remained a simple useful tool for patients to be able to detect skin abnormalities. </li><li>The British Association of Dermatologists also recommends the ABCDE guide to patients as a useful tool to determine which lesions should be reviewed by a healthcare professional:<ul><li><strong>A</strong>symmetry - the two halves of the area may differ in shape.</li><li><strong>B</strong>order - the edges of the area may be irregular or blurred, and sometimes show notches.</li><li><strong>C</strong>olour - this may be uneven. Different shades of black, brown and pink may be seen.</li><li><strong>D</strong>iameter - most melanomas are at least 6mm in diameter. Report any change in size, shape or diameter to your doctor.</li><li><strong>E</strong>xpert - if in doubt, check it out! If your GP is concerned about your skin, make sure you see a Consultant Dermatologist, the most expert person to diagnose a skin cancer. </li></ul></li><li>One study [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/melanoma-pigmented-lesions/references/\">Wolf, 2013</a>] assessed the performance of smartphone applications in the analysis of skin lesions by non-clinical users. The study concluded that the results were highly variable, with sensitivity ranging from 6.8% to 98.1% and specificity, 30.4% to 93.7%. Three out of four of the applications incorrectly diagnosed actual melanomas as benign, potentially delivering a false sense of security to users and potentially cause harm.</li><li>A study by [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/melanoma-pigmented-lesions/references/\">Robinson, 2014</a>] compared the quality of patient education regarding the detection of melanoma via the Internet on a tablet device, paper workbook and In-person education with a facilitator, concluding that there was no superior method and further analysis is required to identify the optimal delivery method.</li></ul><!-- end field 091caf9b-d1ee-4b97-9f80-e8623dccee9c --><!-- end item 419b09bd-785a-4cb2-a6bf-b98f6452efbb -->","topic":{"id":"f5efb7d1-47fd-5e6a-a34d-95395f7523a0","topicId":"c296c560-d236-46ad-abcc-52c1fc0a1abf","topicName":"Melanoma and pigmented lesions","slug":"melanoma-pigmented-lesions","lastRevised":"Last revised in March 2017","chapters":[{"id":"6f710641-b9e2-5edc-aeed-890a7095cd96","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"88e3acd7-3799-5638-93fc-4739079b0f26","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"4cd2dca8-d311-5805-aea1-3870f6f4fccd","fullItemName"